It is up to the Individual to educate yourselves on the issues of people of color ESPECIALLY AND SPECIFICALLY if you intend to roleplay one or create one as a character. To do anything less is an act of willful ignorance and I hold no sympathy or love for you. Good morning!

All this being said, remember I do these threads for free. No one is paying me to continually exert myself attempting to educate an Audience that is perfectly happy remaining obtuse. I do not HAVE to do this. But I am because I don't want to see it happen anymore.

I would say it's my fault for being misled but it really isnt! Meeting people online is not like meeting them irl. Mannerisms, slang banner art icons all form an image around the person that represents who they are and/or what they stand for.
But saying that you arent black will go miles in helping the people watching you deal with and understand your presence in a non harmful way.

Though I loathe to say it, it is the responsibility of non black artists to make explicitly clear their non blackness. Keeping it hidden while continuing to profit and gain fellowship by this online persona for any reason is not a good look. No one needs to know the specifics.

Like giving someone a voice in a community they arent apart of or going unchecked with their portrayal of certain topics and characters. As sad as it is the world does not exist in a vaccuum and neither does art.

To point me in the direction of other black artists and creatives. When you as an rper or artist repeatedly and only use black figures whether they're a beloved oc as your icons without saying who you are, black people will assume you're like us. It can lead to a lot of strife

Been a while since I spoke about this but I want rpers and artists to know that digital black face and digital race faking is real. As a black woman interested in rpg amd art and other niche topics my community is already small. I rely on  pfps and caards and headers -
